Though not specified in the Constitution, voting in the U.S. was mostly limited to white, male landowners. Beginning with the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|fourteenth]] (ratified under duress in 1868), many amendments were added which brought the U.S. closer to a direct democracy: [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment fifteen]] prohibits denial or abridgement, on account of race, color, or previous condition of servitude, of the right to vote. [[Sixteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment sixteen]] gives Congress the power to tax incomes directly. [[Seventeenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment seventeen]] transfers the elective power for senators to the people of their respective states (from the state legislatures). [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment nineteen]] prohibits denial or abridgement, on account of sex, of the right to vote. [[Twenty-third Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment twenty-three]] allows for the participation of the District of Columbia in the election of President and Vice President. [[Twenty-fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment twenty-four]] prohibits denial or abridgement, by reason of failure to pay any poll tax or other tax, of the right to vote in elections for federal office. [[Twenty-sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Amendment twenty-six]] prohibits denial or abridgement, on account of age, of the right of those eighteen years of age or older to vote. [[User:SaltyPig|SaltyPig]] 10:54, 2005 Jun 4 (UTC)

